ir vulnerabilities open a window to assess not only land tenure and property laws but also theoretical approaches to gender and development. Although the development community holds out microcredit financing as one potential solution, these women's stories reveal its glaring limitations. By highlighting the importance of property as a material and symbolic asset in women's empowerment, this book carves out new intellectual space in the study of gender and development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Developing & Emerging Countries.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077481929940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774819299423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774819299/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles